exclude_cols = ['License_Number', 'Hospital_Name', 'Year', 'Quarter', 'State']
numeric_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col not in exclude_cols and df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']]

id_vars = ['Hospital_Name', 'Quarter', 'State']
melted = df.melt(id_vars = id_vars, value_vars = numeric_cols, var_name = 'metric', value_name = 'value')
grouped = melted.groupby(['Hospital_Name', 'Quarter', 'State', 'metric'])['value'].mean().reset_index()
grouped['metric_quarter'] = 'avg_' + grouped['metric'].str.lower() + '_q' + grouped['Quarter'].astype(str)

result = grouped.pivot_table(
    index = ['Hospital_Name', 'State'], 
    columns = 'metric_quarter', 
    values = 'value'
).reset_index()

result.columns.name = None

In [69]:
# Find optimal cluster amount using silhouette score vs inertia
inertia = []
silhouette = []

for k in range(2, 15):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(features_df)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    silh = silhouette_score(features_df, kmeans.labels_)
    silhouette.append(silh)
In [70]:
# Plotting the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(range(2, 15), inertia, marker='o')
plt.title('Inertia vs Number of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.grid(True)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(range(2, 15), silhouette, marker='o', color='orange')
plt.title('Silhouette Score vs Number of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.grid(True)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

  • predominantly urban, major metro areas
  • high dischage and patient days
  • higher average gross receivables and total revenue
  • higher self pay and medicaid volumes

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# axes that best distinguish the clusters
x_col = 'avg_total_revenue_q4'
y_col = 'avg_total_gross_accounts_receivable_q4'

# Plot each cluster with a different color
for cluster in range(kmeans.n_clusters):
    cluster_data = k_means_df[k_means_df['Cluster'] == cluster]
    plt.scatter(
        cluster_data[x_col],
        cluster_data[y_col],
        label=f'Cluster {cluster}',
        s=40,
        alpha=0.7
    )

# Label axes
plt.xlabel('Total Revenue (Q4)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Gross Accounts Receivable (Q4)', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Hospital Clustering by Revenue and Receivables', fontsize=14)
plt.legend()

# annotate a few points
for i, row in k_means_df.iterrows():
    if i % 20 == 0:  # label every 20th hospital to reduce clutter
        plt.text(row[x_col], row[y_col], row['Hospital_Name'], fontsize=7, ha='right')

plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The plot shows the hospitals graphed on a plane that represents total revenue (Q4) and gross accounts recievable (Q4). The color of the points represents the cluster assignments for each hospital using k-means clustering, with cluster 0 (blue points) representing smaller hospitals with overall lower revenues and patients and cluster 1 (orange points) representing hospitals with much higer revenues and amount of pateients.

# Helper function to compute linkage matrix
def compute_linkage(model):
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0])
    n_samples = len(model.labels_)
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_):
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([
        model.children_, 
        model.distances_, 
        counts
    ]).astype(float)
    return linkage_matrix

# Create labels using Hospital_Name and State
labels = meta_df.apply(lambda row: f"{row['Hospital_Name']} ({row['State']})", axis=1).values

# Drop cluster label if still present
X = features_scaled.drop(columns=['Cluster'], errors='ignore')

# Plot dendrograms for different linkage methods
linkages = ['complete', 'single', 'average', 'ward']
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 14))

for ax, method in zip(axs.flat, linkages):
    model = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None, linkage=method)
    model = model.fit(X)
    Z = compute_linkage(model)

    ax.set_title(f"Linkage: {method.capitalize()}", fontsize=14)
    dendrogram(Z, ax=ax, labels=labels, leaf_rotation=90, leaf_font_size=6)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=6)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Define function to evaluate silhouette scores for different cluster counts
def evaluate_clusters_silhouette(X, linkage_matrix, max_clusters=10):
    silhouette_scores = []
    cluster_range = range(2, max_clusters + 1)
    
    for n_clusters in cluster_range:
        cluster_labels = fcluster(linkage_matrix, n_clusters, criterion='maxclust')
        score = silhouette_score(X, cluster_labels)
        silhouette_scores.append(score)
    
    return cluster_range, silhouette_scores
    
# Drop 'Cluster' column if exists
X = features_scaled.drop(columns=['Cluster'], errors='ignore')

# Fit Complete linkage model
model_complete = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None, linkage='complete')
model_complete = model_complete.fit(X)
link_complete = compute_linkage(model_complete)
range_complete, scores_complete = evaluate_clusters_silhouette(X, link_complete)

# Fit Ward linkage model
model_ward = AgglomerativeClustering(distance_threshold=0, n_clusters=None, linkage='ward')
model_ward = model_ward.fit(X)
link_ward = compute_linkage(model_ward)
range_ward, scores_ward = evaluate_clusters_silhouette(X, link_ward)

Hierarchical CLustering using the ward method optimally splits the hospitals into two clusters that likely represents hospital characteristics like care complexity and size of instituion. Cluster 1 includes 28 hospitals, which generally are large, urban, or university affliliated hospitals. Many are major regional medical centers with familar names like Seattle Chidren's Hospital, Sweedish, Virgina Mason and so forth. These hospitals are likely characterized by their high patitnet voumnes and wide range of services offered. Cluster 2 includes smaller, more rural or community based hospitals like Arbor Health and Providence Seaside. Some of these hospitals also provied specialied care like Fred Hutchinson Cancer center specializing in cancer and BHC Fairfax specializing in mental health. These types of hospitals are characterized by fewer beds, lower discharge volumnes, smaller overall insitution whether it be due to geographic location or hospital specialization.
